04994nam a22006615i 9780520927117DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20201999cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209271177 a10.1525/97805209271172doi  a(DE-B1597)543001  a(OCoLC)1163878923  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aDS558b.L6 1999 7aHIS0360002bisacsh04a959.704/33732211 aLogevall, Fredrik, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aChoosing War :bThe Lost Chance for Peace and the Escalation of War in Vietnam /cFredrik Logevall.  aReprint 2019 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2020] 4c©1999  a1 online resource (560 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tPreface -- tAbbreviations Used in the Text -- t1. The Kickoff: 29 August 1963 -- t2. Breaks and Continuities: September to November 1963 -- t3. "I Will Not Lose in Vietnam": November 1963 to January 1964 -- t4. "A Deeply Dangerous Game": February to April 1964 -- t5. Rumblings of Discontent: April to June 1964 -- t6. Campaigns at Home and Abroad: June and July 1964 -- t7. Provocations: August 1964 -- t8. Standing Logic on Its Head: September and October 1964 -- t9. The Freedom to Change: November and December 1964 -- t10. "Stable Government or No Stable Government": January and February 1965 -- t11. Americanization: February to July 1965 -- t12. Choosing War -- tAbbreviations Used in the Notes -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn one of the most detailed and powerfully argued books published on American intervention in Vietnam, Fredrik Logevall examines the last great unanswered question on the war: Could the tragedy have been averted? His answer: a resounding yes. Challenging the prevailing myth that the outbreak of large-scale fighting in 1965 was essentially unavoidable, Choosing War argues that the Vietnam War was unnecessary, not merely in hindsight but in the context of its time. Why, then, did major war break out? Logevall shows it was partly because of the timidity of the key opponents of U.S. involvement, and partly because of the staunch opposition of the Kennedy and Johnson administrations to early negotiations. His superlative account shows that U.S. officials chose war over disengagement despite deep doubts about the war's prospects and about Vietnam's importance to U.S. security and over the opposition of important voices in the Congress, in the press, and in the world community. They did so because of concerns about credibility—not so much America's or the Democratic party's credibility, but their own personal credibility. Based on six years of painstaking research, this book is the first to place American policymaking on Vietnam in 1963-65 in its wider international context using multiarchival sources, many of them recently declassified. Here we see for the first time how the war played in the key world capitals—not merely in Washington, Saigon, and Hanoi, but also in Paris and London, in Tokyo and Ottawa, in Moscow and Beijing. Choosing War is a powerful and devastating account of fear, favor, and hypocrisy at the highest echelons of American government, a book that will change forever our understanding of the tragedy that was the Vietnam War.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aVietnam War, 1961-1975zUnited States. 4aAsian history. 4aDemocratic Party. 4aVietnam War. 4aVietnam. 4ahistory of the Americas. 4ahistory. 4amilitary history. 4asecurity. 4awar. 7aHISTORY / United States / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z9783110635348